The Slave Trade of Aetheria: Chains of Flesh and Profit
Slavery is a fundamental and accepted part of life across Aetheria. In a world of endless low-level conflict, raids, debt, and harsh survival, the buying and selling of sentient beings is seen as an economic necessity by most societies rather than a moral evil. The slave trade is a vast, dangerous, and highly profitable network that spans continents. Slaves are acquired through warfare, raids, debt bondage, criminal punishment, and breeding. Markets range from open-air auction blocks in human cities to secretive spirit-bound contracts in elven groves.
While large-scale racial wars are rare, small raids between races (and within them) provide a steady supply of fresh captives. Slave caravans are heavily guarded, as escaped slaves, rival traders, and opportunistic bandits make the routes perilous. Prices vary wildly depending on age, skills, race, appearance, and magical aptitude.
The Human Kingdoms (The Fifteen Realms)
Humans operate the largest, most organized, and most openly commercial slave trade on the continent. Slavery is fully legal and regulated in all fifteen kingdoms, though rules differ slightly by region.
Main Sources:

Prisoners from internal wars between kingdoms and marches.
Beastkin captured in border raids.
Debtors who sell themselves or their families.
Criminals (thieves, deserters, rebels) sentenced to penal slavery.
Orphaned or sold children from poor families.
Occasional elven or dwarven captives (rare and expensive).

Key Markets:

The great auction city of Vael’s Landing (former Vel’thorne territory) is the largest slave market in the human lands.
Marcher border towns host rougher, cheaper markets full of Beastkin and demon-tainted captives.

Uses and Treatment:

Domestic slaves (most common) work households, farms, mines and sex.
Martial slaves (especially Beastkin) serve as gladiators, arena fighters, or auxiliary troops.
Skilled slaves (dwarven smiths, elven scribes, mages) command premium prices and better treatment.
Bloodline slaves (Elven, Pretty Beastkin) serve a few noble houses as a means to an end. Elven mages to introduce more magic aptitude into the noble house's decendends (First generation produces Half-elves). Mainly cat, fox and rabbit beastfolk are also use by some nobles to beastify their bloodline. Decendents become hybrids humans with beast features, tail, claws, animal ears, etc...
Human slaves are the cheapest and most numerous. Beastkin males are prized for strength; females for exotic appeal. Elves are status symbols — owning one is a sign of wealth and power.
Even cheaper than Humans are hybrids and half-breeds abandoned or sold (quite common for various reasons, but specially to pay for debts) by noble houses. These are not accepted by neither of their blood races.

Conditions vary by owner. Marcher lords (and their vassals) and wealthy merchants often treat slaves brutally, while some southern kingdoms have laws protecting “valuable” slaves from excessive harm. Escaped slaves are hunted by specialized Slave-Takers Guilds.
The Elven Enclaves (High Forest and Wildwood)
Elves practice a more ritualistic and paternalistic form of slavery they rarely call “slavery” openly. They prefer terms like Bound Service, Blood Debt, or Root-Tied.
Main Sources:

Humans and Beastkin captured in retaliatory raids.
Criminals within their own society (exile is more common, but serious offenders can be bound).
Occasionally dwarves or rival elves.

Key Practices:

High Forest Enclaves use enchanted vine collars or spirit oaths that prevent escape and enforce obedience. Breaking the bond can cause agonizing pain or death.
Slaves are often “civilized” through long-term magical education and indoctrination. Many eventually earn limited freedom or become permanent lower-caste servants.
Wildwood Exiles are far harsher — captives may be used in blood rituals, hunting games, or sacrificed to nature spirits.

Uses:

Labor in living groves and gardens.
Personal attendants to nobles.
Military auxiliaries (especially captured Beastkin warriors).
Rare magical talents are studied and exploited.

Elves consider enslaving other elves deeply taboo (though it still happens in secret). Owning a human is common among the aristocracy; owning a dwarf is seen as eccentric or shameful.
The Dwarven Holds
Dwarven slavery is practical, clan-based, and heavily tied to labor shortages in the deep mines and forges. They call slaves Stone-Bound or Debt-Owed.
Main Sources:

Captives from underground wars against demons and rival clans.
Debtors who cannot repay loans to powerful clans.
Criminals sentenced to hard labor.
Surface raids (mostly humans and Beastkin).

Key Features:

Slaves are almost exclusively used for dangerous, back-breaking labor: mining unstable veins, working the hottest forges, or clearing collapsed tunnels.
Dwarven law demands that slaves be fed and housed adequately (“A broken tool serves no one”), but conditions in the deepest holds are still lethal.
Skilled slaves (especially other dwarves or talented human engineers) can earn their freedom after decades of service, or even be adopted into a minor branch of a clan.
Beastkin are valued for their strength but watched closely due to their volatile tempers.

Dwarves rarely keep surface slaves long-term — most are worked hard, sold onward, or released once their debt is considered paid. Demon-tainted slaves are immediately executed.
The Beastkin Tribes and Confederations
Beastkin slavery is the most chaotic and brutal. It is rarely a formalized “trade” and more often a matter of conquest and dominance.
Main Sources:

Captives from raids on other clans (especially rival predator/prey tribes).
Humans taken from border villages.
Weak members of their own tribes sold during hard seasons.
Demon-corrupted individuals kept as living warnings.

Practices:

Slavery among Beastkin is highly personal. A captured warrior might be forced to fight in ritual combats or serve as a pack subordinate until they earn respect or die.
The Golden Pride maintains large slave pools for labor and breeding programs to strengthen bloodlines.
Serpentis Dominion uses slaves extensively in jungle plantations and for blood rituals.
Many tribes practice Rite of the Broken Fang — a ritual combat where slaves can earn freedom by defeating their captor.

Beastkin slaves in human lands are common, but free Beastkin rarely buy slaves themselves, preferring to kill or integrate captives through dominance displays.
The Demonic Territories
Demonic slavery is by far the worst in Aetheria. To demons, mortals are resources — bodies, souls, and entertainment.
Main Sources:

All mortal races captured in raids.
Mortal traitors and cultists who willingly submit.
Bred slave lineages (multi-generational human/demonic hybrids).

Key Features:

Highblood demons (succubi, incubi, etc.) keep elegant pleasure slaves and status servants.
Monstrous demons use mortals as food, breeding stock, or raw material for flesh-crafting.
Soul-binding contracts are common — far stronger than elven vine collars.
Gladiator pits, soul-forges, and corruption experiments consume thousands annually.

Demons regularly sell excess slaves to mortal traders (especially unscrupulous human merchants) in exchange for rare materials, information, or magical artifacts.
The Cross-Racial Slave Trade
A shadowy network of Neutral Traders (mostly human merchant houses, certain gnome and halfling clans, and opportunistic Beastkin) operates in the Buffer Zones and Free Cities. They buy cheap slaves in one region and sell them at a markup elsewhere. The most valuable commodities are:

Young, attractive elves
Strong Beastkin warriors
Master crafts-dwarves
Mages of any race
Young, attractive beastkin (Bloodline slaves)

Slavery remains a major point of tension between races. A raid that captures dozens can spark decades of blood feuds, even while larger wars are avoided. Many adventurers and hedge knights make their living as slave hunters, liberators, or escorts for slave caravans.
In this fractured world, the chains of Aetheria are as common as iron and as enduring as ancient grudges.
